    "correct": 0,
    "explanation": "First, let's calculate the total profit for the year by summing up the monthly net amounts:\n\n1. Rs. 5,000 profit\n2. Rs. -2,000 loss\n3. Rs. 7,000 profit\n4. Rs. 1,000 profit\n5. Rs. -3,000 loss\n6. Rs. 10,000 profit\n7. Rs. 500 profit\n8. Rs. 4,000 profit\n9. Rs. -2,500 loss\n10. Rs. 6,000 profit\n11. Rs. 8,000 profit\n12. Rs. -1,000 loss\n\nTotal profit = Rs. 5,000 - Rs. 2,000 + Rs. 7,000 + Rs. 1,000 - Rs. 3,000 + Rs. 10,000 + Rs. 500 + Rs. 4,000 - Rs. 2,500 + Rs. 6,000 + Rs. 8,000 - Rs. 1,000\nTotal profit = Rs. 42,000\n\nNext, we need to calculate the ratio of their investments considering the time each person was involved in the business.\n\nTom invested Rs. 30,000 for 12 months.\nJose invested Rs. 45,000 but joined 2 months later, so he invested for 10 months.\nMaria invested Rs. 60,000 but joined 4 months later, so she invested for 8 months.\n\nTom's investment ratio = Rs. 30,000 * 12 = Rs. 360,000\nJose's investment ratio = Rs. 45,000 * 10 = Rs. 450,000\nMaria's investment ratio = Rs. 60,000 * 8 = Rs. 480,000\n\nTotal investment ratio = Rs. 360,000 + Rs. 450,000 + Rs. 480,000\nTotal investment ratio = Rs. 1,290,000\n\nNow, we find the share of each person in the total profit based on their investment ratio.\n\nTom's share = (Rs. 360,000 / Rs. 1,290,000) * Rs. 42,000\nJose's share = (Rs. 450,000 / Rs. 1,290,000) * Rs. 42,000\nMaria's share = (Rs. 480,000 / Rs. 1,290,000) * Rs. 42,000\n\nLet's calculate Jose's share:\n\nJose's share = (Rs. 450,000 / Rs. 1,290,000) * Rs. 42,000\nJose's share = (450 / 1290) * Rs. 42,000\nJose's share = (5 / 14.3333) * Rs. 42,000\nJose's share = 0.3490 * Rs. 42,000\nJose's share = Rs. 14,658 (approximately)\n\nTherefore, Jose's share of the overall profit at the end of the year is approximately Rs. 14,658.",
