    "id": 1217,
    "question": "Bert and Tory started a two-day competition to see who could sell more toys at a local fair. On the first day, Bert sold toy phones and Tory sold toy guns. Bert started by selling 12 toy phones for $18 each, while Tory sold 15 toy guns for $20 each. However, during the first half of the day, Bert gave a 15% discount on 3 of his toy phones and Tory had to offer a 10% discount on 5 of his toy guns. \n\nOn the second day, they decided to swap their selling items. Now, Bert decided to sell toy guns while Tory sold toy phones. Bert sold his toy guns for £15 each and managed to sell 10 of them. Tory, however, sold her toy phones for £18 each and sold 8 of these phones on the second day. \n\nHowever, the challenge got trickier when they had to consider a local tax of 5% on the selling price of each toy and a fluctuating currency exchange rate. On the first day, the exchange rate was $1.3/£, and on the second day, it was $1.4/£. \n\nConsidering all these dynamics, how much more in USD did Bert earn than Tory at the end of the two-day competition?\n\n### Answer:",
