    "explanation": "Let's start by calculating the population of Youngsville in the year 2010 after the growth spurt.\n\nPopulation in 2000 = 684 people\nGrowth in population in 2010 = 25% of 684\n\nPopulation increase = 0.25 * 684 = 171 people\n\nPopulation in 2010 = 684 + 171 = 855 people\n\nNow, let's calculate the number of males and females in 2010, assuming the gender ratio remained the same as in 2000.\n\nMales in 2010 = 55% of 855 = 0.55 * 855 = 470.25\nSince we can't have a fraction of a person, we'll round this to 470 males.\n\nFemales in 2010 = 45% of 855 = 0.45 * 855 = 384.75\nSimilarly, we'll round this to 385 females.\n\nNext, let's calculate the population in each age group in 2010.\n\nUnder 18 in 2010 = 25% of 855 = 0.25 * 855 = 213.75\nWe'll round this to 214 people under 18.\n\nAged 18-59 in 2010 = 60% of 855 = 0.60 * 855 = 513 people\n\nAged 60 and older in 2010 = 15% of 855 = 0.15 * 855 = 128.25\nWe'll round this to 128 people aged 60 and older.\n\nNow, let's calculate the population in 2015 after the economic downturn.\n\nPopulation decrease in 2015 = 40% of 855\n\nPopulation decrease = 0.40 * 855 = 342 people\n\nPopulation in 2015 = 855 - 342 = 513 people\n\nThe gender ratio remains the same, so:\n\nMales in 2015 = 55% of 513 = 0.55 * 513 = 282.15\nWe'll round this to 282 males.\n\nFemales in 2015 = 45% of 513 = 0.45 * 513 = 230.85\nWe'll round this to 231 females.\n\nFinally, let's calculate the population in each age group in 2015.\n\nUnder 18 in 2015 = 20% of 513 = 0.20 * 513 = 102.6\nWe'll round this to 103 people under 18.\n\nAged 18-59 in 2015 = 65% of 513 = 0.65 * 513 = 333.45\nWe'll round this to 333 people aged 18-59.\n\nAged 60 and older in 2015 = 15% of 513 = 0.15 * 513 = 76.95\nWe'll round this to 77 people aged 60 and older.\n\nTo summarize, the current population of Youngsville in the year 2015 is 513 people, with 282 males and 231 females. The headcount in each age group is 103 people under 18, 333 people aged 18-59, and 77 people aged 60 and older.",
