    "question": "Nikola is saving up for a bag of ant food before he can start his ant farm. He wants 400 ants in his farm, which requires 1 kg of food. To create a balanced diet, the ant food mix needs 60% food type A and 40% food type B. Every kg of type A ant food costs $9, while every kg of type B ant food costs $12. However, during a seasonal sale, type A food is discounted by 10% and type B food by 5%.\n\nNikola is saving up by raking leaves. He charges $5 to start a job and then charges by the leaf. Each maple leaf he rakes costs 1 penny, while each oak leaf he rakes costs 1.5 pennies. He offers a discount of 5% for raking more than 1,000 leaves in a single job and an additional 2% if the customer also wants the leaves bagged.\n\nOn average, Nikola can rake 50 leaves per hour. Some customers also require him to work during specific time slots, such as mornings (8 AM - 12 PM) or afternoons (1 PM - 5 PM).\n\nNikola finally saved up enough money after completing the following jobs:\n\n1. A 600-maple-leaf job, taking 4 hours, during a morning time slot.\n2. A 1,200-oak-leaf job, taking 5 hours, with the 5% discount for leaf quantity and an additional 2% discount for bagging leaves.\n3. A 900-maple-leaf and 300-oak-leaf job, taking 6 hours, during an afternoon time slot.\n\nDuring the seasonal sale, how much money does Nikola need to save for a balanced diet of ant food? How many jobs did he complete to earn this money? How many of the jobs had more than 1,000 leaves? And how many of the jobs had specific time slot requirements?\n\n### Answer:",
