    "explanation": "To estimate the total number of fish for each species in the pond, we can use the mark and recapture method. This method assumes that the proportion of tagged fish in the sample is the same as the proportion of tagged fish in the entire population.\n\nLet's denote the total number of fish for each species in the pond as \\( N_A \\) for Species A, \\( N_B \\) for Species B, and \\( N_C \\) for Species C.\n\nFirst, we need to calculate the total number of tagged fish for each species after Day 2:\n\nSpecies A: 30 (Day 1) + 40 (Day 2) = 70 tagged fish\nSpecies B: 25 (Day 1) + 35 (Day 2) = 60 tagged fish\nSpecies C: 25 (Day 1) + 25 (Day 2) = 50 tagged fish\n\nNext, we'll use the data from Day 3 and Day 4 to estimate the total population. We'll average the percentages of tagged fish from both days for a more accurate estimate.\n\nFor Species A:\nDay 3: 4 tagged out of 60 caught = 4/60 = 1/15\nDay 4: 5 tagged out of 70 caught = 5/70 = 1/14\nAverage proportion tagged = (1/15 + 1/14) / 2 = (14 + 15) / (15 * 14 * 2) = 29 / (210 * 2) = 29 / 420\n\\( N_A = \\) Total tagged / Average proportion tagged = 70 / (29 / 420) = 70 * (420 / 29) ≈ 70 * 14.48 ≈ 1013.6 ≈ 1014 fish\n\nFor Species B:\nDay 3: 6 tagged out of 50 caught = 6/50 = 3/25\nDay 4: 7 tagged out of 40 caught = 7/40 = 7/40\nAverage proportion tagged = (3/25 + 7/40) / 2 = (120 + 175) / (1000 * 2) = 295 / 2000\n\\( N_B = \\) Total tagged / Average proportion tagged = 60 / (295 / 2000) = 60 * (2000 / 295) ≈ 60 * 6.78 ≈ 406.8 ≈ 407 fish\n\nFor Species C:\nDay 3: 2 tagged out of 30 caught = 2/30 = 1/15\nDay 4: 3 tagged out of 50 caught = 3/50 = 3/50\nAverage proportion tagged = (1/15 + 3/50) / 2 = (50 + 45) / (750 * 2) = 95 / 1500\n\\( N_C = \\) Total tagged / Average proportion tagged = 50 / (95 / 1500) = 50 * (1500 / 95) ≈ 50 * 15.79 ≈ 789.5 ≈ 790 fish\n\nTherefore, the estimated total number of fish for each species in the pond is approximately:\nSpecies A: 1014 fish\nSpecies B: 407 fish\nSpecies C: 790 fish",
