    "id": 1234,
    "question": "Over a period of 5 years, the rabbit population in Lola's house underwent several changes. In the first spring, Lola's 10 breeding rabbits had 10 times as many kittens as the number of breeding rabbits. Half of the kittens got adopted, but 5 of them had to be returned to Lola due to re-homing problems.\n\nIn the second spring, her 12 breeding rabbits had a total of 90 kittens, with 40% of the kittens being adopted. However, 10 of those adopted kittens were returned a few weeks later. Meanwhile, two breeding rabbits retired, reducing the breeding rabbit population to 10.\n\nIn the third spring, Lola's now 10 breeding rabbits had a total of 75 kittens. This time, 30% of the kittens got adopted and 7 returned back to Lola. Two more breeding rabbits were removed due to age, reducing the breeding rabbit count to 8.\n\nDuring the fourth spring, with 8 breeding rabbits left, they had 5 kittens each, with 20% being successfully adopted and 4 being returned due to re-homing challenges. Five new rabbits were introduced to the breeding pool, raising the total to 13 breeding rabbits.\n\nFinally, in the fifth spring, the 13 breeding rabbits had an average of 6 kittens each, and 25% of the kittens were adopted, but 6 were later brought back to Lola for various reasons.\n\nIncluding the breeding rabbits, how many rabbits does Lola have in her house after the fifth spring?\n\n### Answer:",
