    "id": 1244,
    "question": "In a three-day MLB game between Team A and Team B, the ratio of misses to hits and types of hits varies each day for both teams. On the first day, Team A has twice as many misses as hits (with 60 misses), while Team B has three times as many misses as hits (with 90 misses). For each team, half of their hits on the first day are home runs and the other half are singles.\n\nOn the second day, Team A has four times as many misses as hits (with 68 misses), while Team B has two times as many misses as hits (with 56 misses). On this day, one-third of each team's hits are doubles and the remainder are singles.\n\nOn the third day, the ratio of misses to hits for both teams is 5:1. Team A has 100 misses, and Team B has 120 misses. For third day hits of both teams, one-fourth are triples, one-fourth are home runs, and the remaining hits are singles.\n\nCalculate the combined total of misses, singles, doubles, triples, and home runs for Team A and Team B made during the entire three-day game.\n\n### Answer:",
