    "correct": 0,
    "explanation": "Let's start by setting up equations for each type of fruit based on the information given.\n\nFor pears:\n- The number of pears canned = (5/4)x more than poached\n- The number of pears poached = (2/3)x less than sold\n\nFor apples:\n- The number of apples canned = (11/10)y more than poached\n- The number of apples poached = (3/4)y less than sold\n\nFor oranges:\n- The number of oranges canned = (4/3)z more than poached\n- The number of oranges poached = (1/3)z less than sold\n\nNow, let's denote the number of pears poached as P_poached, the number of apples poached as A_poached, and the number of oranges poached as O_poached.\n\nFor pears:\nP_poached = x - (2/3)x = (1/3)x\nP_canned = P_poached + (5/4)x = (1/3)x + (5/4)x\n\nFor apples:\nA_poached = y - (3/4)y = (1/4)y\nA_canned = A_poached + (11/10)y = (1/4)y + (11/10)y\n\nFor oranges:\nO_poached = z - (1/3)z = (2/3)z\nO_canned = O_poached + (4/3)z = (2/3)z + (4/3)z\n\nNow, we know the total number of each fruit, so we can set up the following equations:\n\nFor pears (total 75):\nx + (1/3)x + (1/3)x + (5/4)x = 75\n\nFor apples (total 60):\ny + (1/4)y + (1/4)y + (11/10)y = 60\n\nFor oranges (total 45):\nz + (2/3)z + (2/3)z + (4/3)z = 45\n\nLet's solve these equations one by one.\n\nFor pears:\nx + (1/3)x + (5/4)x = 75\n(1 + 1/3 + 5/4)x = 75\n(4/4 + 4/12 + 15/12)x = 75\n(12/12 + 4/12 + 15/12)x = 75\n(31/12)x = 75\nx = 75 * (12/31)\nx = 900/31\nx ≈ 29 pears sold\n\nFor apples:\ny + (1/4)y + (11/10)y = 60\n(1 + 1/4 + 11/10)y = 60\n(4/4 + 1/4 + 11/10)y = 60\n(10/10 + 2.5/10 + 11/10)y = 60\n(23.5/10)y = 60\ny = 60 * (10/23.5)\ny = 600/23.5\ny ≈ 26 apples sold\n\nFor oranges:\nz + (2/3)z + (4/3)z = 45\n(1 + 2/3 + 4/3)z = 45\n(3/3 + 2/3 + 4/3)z = 45\n(9/3)z = 45\nz = 45 * (3/9)\nz = 45 * (1/3)\nz = 15 oranges sold\n\nSo, the values of x, y, and z are approximately 29, 26, and 15, respectively.",
