    "question": "A father is building a customized playset for his two children and needs to purchase lumber, nails, fabric, paint, and rope. When he started planning the project, the necessary lumber cost $450, the nails cost $30, the fabric cost $80, the paint cost $60, and the rope cost $40. The first child wishes to add a swing, costing an additional $100, while the second child prefers a slide costing $150.\n\nHowever, recent economic inflation and market fluctuations have caused the prices to change over the past three months. In the first month, the price of lumber increased by 20%, the price of nails increased by 10%, and the price of fabric increased by 5%, while the price of paint and rope remained the same. In the second month, the price of paint increased by 10%, and the price of rope increased by 15%, while the price of lumber, nails, and fabric remained the same. In the third month, the cost of the swing increased by 8%, and the cost of the slide increased by 12%.\n\nCalculate the new total cost of creating the playset with each child's preference after all price changes in the past three months. Compare the new total costs to the original total costs before the inflation and fluctuations and determine how much more money, in dollars, it will cost to complete the project now (after all changes) than it would have when the father began planning.\n\n### Answer:",
